AB  - This report provides an overview of the storm impacts during the Northwest Monsoon season of 2019 in Seychelles. Two storms in December 2019 caused severe overtopping and erosion impacts in the islands of Mahe and Praslin. The events were associated to a swell generated by a depression in the Indian Ocean, the first one of which later strengthened to become Cyclone Berna in the western Indian Ocean. This storm was followed by another one that coincided with even higher tide levels and also produced flooding and erosion impacts. The storms produced flooding and substantial erosion of sandy beaches, damage to the vegetation line and caused widespread damages to sea walls, rock armoring, road infrastructure, hotels and properties. Wave action atop high sea level conditions during December 2019 were the plausible causes of most of the observed severe beach erosion and impacts. The flooding levels would have at least exceeded 2 m above mean sea level during these storms. The most impacted areas were northwest and north Praslin and northwest Mahe, including in Praslin: Cote D’Or, Anse la Blague, Anse Lazio, Anse Kerlan, Grand Anse, among others; and in Mahe: Beau Vallon and North East Point. Wave modeling results for the storms in December 2019 and those during the Southeast Monsoon season indicate substantial differences in the coastlines affected depending on storm conditions. The wave modeling results also explain the impacts based on the direction and intensity of wave action in areas with the highest observed impacts: north and northwest Praslin and Northwest of Mahe. The quantification of the economic damage caused by the storms would need further analysis. However, it is estimated that over 1,000 buildings and 27 hotels are located within areas that were affected by flooding and by erosion, which are at higher risk since these storms. The recommendations are aligned with the priorities identified in the Coastal Management Plan 2019-2022, which include investments in infrastructure and nature-based solutions for coastal protection as well as increased attention to capacity building of the implementing agencies responsible for coastal protection in Seychelles. This impact assessment report should be considered supplementary to the Coastal Management Plan.
