AB  - Organic carbon stored in coastal vegetated habitats, such as salt marshes, mangroves, and seagrasses, is defined as blue carbon. The conservation of seagrasses is considered as a nature-based solution to mitigate climate change, and blue carbon assessments may support decision making. This study focuses on mapping and assessing blue carbon storage and sequestration by the seagrass Cymodocea nodosa in the oceanic region of the Canary Islands (eastern Atlantic). Particularly, this study: (1) mapped and assessed the past and current capacity of C. nodosa to store and sequester blue carbon with high spatial resolution (20 m/pixel), (2) mapped and assessed blue carbon under four plausible future scenarios (“No Net Loss”, “Intermediate”, “Business-as-usual” and “Collapse”), and (3) valued the economic implications of these scenarios. The seagrass C. nodosa has suffered ca. 50% area loss in the last two decades, and, if the current degradation rate continues, our estimations demonstrate that it could completely disappear in 2036 (“Collapse”). The impact of these losses in 2050 would reach 1.43 Megatonnes of CO2 equivalent emitted (45% from the current situation) with a cost of 126.3 million € (0.32% of the current Canary GDP). If, however, this degradation is slow down, between 0.11 and 0.57 MT of CO2 equivalent would be emitted until 2050 (“Intermediate” and “Business-as-usual” scenarios, respectively), which corresponds to a social cost of 3.63 and 44.81 million €, respectively. If the decline would be stopped, and the current seagrass extension maintained (“No Net Loss”), 0.75 MT of CO2 equivalent would be sequestered from now to 2050, which corresponds to a social cost saving of 73.59 million €. The main areas and human pressures that need to be tackled were identified to facilitate decision-making. This research proposes, therefore, a methodological strategy with potential applicability across coastal vegetated ecosystems.
