AB  - Biodiversity is a key indicator of ecosystem health and plays an important role in providing the ecosystem services essential for economic development and social well-being. In Ireland, climate change and anthropogenic pressures have resulted in biodiversity loss and habitat degradation, with knock-on effects on the provision of ecosystem services. The aim of this study was to determine how coastal marine biodiversity and ecosystem services in the Republic of Ireland are represented in the scientific literature, news media, and current legislation. A review of the scientific literature revealed limited research related to coastal marine biodiversity and the number of publications was even lower for ecosystem services. To date, the main lines of research on coastal marine biodiversity have been the abundance and community structure of benthic organisms, such as algae and invertebrates, while ecosystem services research has primarily been associated with coastal zone management. Analysis of the news media indicated that coverage of biodiversity and ecosystem services has increased in the last decade but is far lower than that for topics such as climate change. The terms biodiversity and ecosystem services have only been incorporated into Irish legislation in recent years, and mainly correspond to the transposition of European Directives. Despite evidence of the importance of biodiversity for the sustained provision of ecosystem services, important knowledge gaps remain. Here, we examine those gaps and evaluate current efforts towards greater understanding of coastal marine biodiversity and ecosystem services.
